On 1/27/21 3:35 PM, Greg A. Woods wrote:
> Thanks!  (but I still need to pester my service provider for rDNS!)

You're welcome.

> Sorry, I should have been a tiny bit more specific:  the "user=20
> interface" here refers to a Graphical UI.  Unix of course didn't start =

> out with a GUI of any kind, and workstation vendors like Sun and many=20
> others at the time made a big deal out of how they were offering a=20
> better user interface for their systems.

Hum ...

> I separate "kernel" and "userland" (here meaning all the command-line=20
> programs, etc.) only because that's become a more common way to define =

> the "base OS" in unixy, i.e. linuxy, circles.

When I think of Base OS, I think of AIX, because it's the first place I=20
saw Base OS, referred to as BOS, explicitly called out.  But, I know=20
that Solaris and HP-UX also have a very minimal install.  Even Linux has =

very minimal installs (debootstrap, Slackware boot+root, and DSL come to =

mind).

I think of development applications / compilers, fancy text processing,=20
networking, X11, office applications as all being add on products.=20
Sure, Linux tends to come with a LOT of them installed by default.

I guess the base OS to me is what's required to boot, maintain, and=20
install a system.  Anything else is ancillary as far as -- what I=20
consider to be -- the base OS is concerned.

> This distinction between the traditional Unix layer and the GUI is=20
> quite important in the history of SunOS, since there have been a number=
=20
> of different offerings from Sun for their GUI (Sun Windowing System,=20
> SunView, NeWS, SunWindows); and also in how Sun promoted their various =

> GUI offerings as the solutions for wider use.

Hum.  I guess my exposure to Solaris installations has tainted my view.=20
I helped support some DB servers with the full GUI developers=20
workstation installed, just in case it was needed.  The people that=20
installed them didn't want to ever go back and pull something else in.=20
Which is why we had to patch Firefox, Thunderbird, and Pidgen /=20
libpurple on Solaris database servers.  At least until I ripped those=20
things, along with the kitchen sink, out.  It made patching so much=20
faster and smaller.

> Even with the advent of a common choice of The X Window System as the=20
> basis for most workstation vendor's GUIs, there were still battles=20
> over which toolkit and window manager and "look and feel" would prevail=
=20
> (Athena vs. Motif vs. OpenLook), with Sun even evolving their offerings=
=20
> (SunWindows, OpenLook) over time.

I'm vaguely aware of CDE and that there were others before / around=20
that.  But my personal experience is largely after that.  As such, I=20
wasn't aware of some of the things that you are talking about.  Thank=20
you for enlightening me.



